Resolves a chain's nodes (rollups, intent, leaf) to actual content for CLI/hook consumption, substituting a soft one-line `(absent: …)` marker for any missing file rather than erroring — sparse scaffolding (no per-directory rollup/intent guarantee) is a normal state, not a failure. The only hard error is an unreadable-but-present file or an invalid path.

`chain_for<E: Env>(env: &E, raw: &str) -> Result<Vec<ServedNode>, CtxError>` parses `raw` (via `parse_target`, where `"."` means repo root and trailing `/` is stripped), decides directory-vs-file chain shape by calling `env.is_dir`, then delegates to `chain::for_dir`/`chain::for_file` and serves each returned `ChainNode` with `serve_one`. A directory target yields rollup+intent chain down to itself; a file target appends its leaf `<file>.ctx`.

`fresh_chain_for<E: Env>(env: &E, session_id: &str, raw: &str) -> Result<Option<Vec<ServedNode>>, CtxError>` layers session-dedup on top: loads the set of node ids already shown this session via `session::load`, filters them out of the freshly computed chain, and returns `Ok(None)` if nothing *present* remains (absent markers alone don't count as worth showing, even if they're "new"). On any remaining present node it updates and persists the served-set via `session::save`. This is the shared gate ensuring hook-mode and CLI-mode invocations never redundantly re-show the same node within a session, and repeat calls are idempotent no-ops once everything's been served — the coupling here is with `session.rs`'s ledger format/load/save semantics.

`ServedNode` carries `id` (repo-relative string), `kind: NodeKind`, `body` (UTF-8-lossy file contents or the absent marker), and `present: bool` (false iff body is a marker). `render(nodes: &[ServedNode]) -> String` formats each as a `=== id [kind-label] ===` header followed by body, force-appending a trailing newline if the body lacks one — this is the actual on-disk/stdout text format consumers see, so changing the header format affects any downstream parsing of ctx output.